A few weeks ago, I was seeing disconnects due to timeouts, esp. against the JaaS controllers. That was fixed as of v 0.4.1.

We still may get disconnects just due to random network issues. I don't think that it's appropriate to try to reconnect from within python-libjuju, however. There isn't a way to pick up the websocket connection where you left off, and python-libjuju can't really tell which requests have been processed on the juju side, and which have been dropped.

@battlemidget I think that the best solution here is to catch the ConnectionClosed exception in conjure-up, either alerting the user that something went wrong, or trying to pick up on the deploy process where you think that you have lost the connection.

@giuscri if you install pipenv with `--prefix=/usr/local`, then you need to put `/usr/local/bin` on your path to make sure you are interacting with the correct pipenv.  If you universally put `/usr/local/lib/python3.6/site-packages` on your `PYTHONPATH` environment variable, then yes, every python installation everywhere on your system will always have access to those packages.

The `PATH` variable allows your system to find executables.  The `PYTHONPATH` variable tells your python runtime where to find python packages.  Overriding the latter is usually not what you want

Thanks for using pipenv!

@begoldsm , @jbcrail : please review.
The code now uses ADAL exclusively as before, but the refresh portion is now in the REST layer and checked for expiry on every call. The type of token created will depend on the set of credentials supplied, and a token generated in ADAL by other means should work too.

User/password credentials will auto-refresh, and client/secret ones will error after expiry (we don't store the secret).

