@stefanocovino I got it :). The bug is that ``BasicPSFPhotometry`` is changing your ``pos`` so that it adds a ``flux_0`` column in ``pos`` which shouldn't be added.

I am going to open a pull request for this in the next few days. In the meantime, you can just repeat ``pos = Table(names=['x_0', 'y_0'], data=[[X-np.rint(X)+size],[Y-np.rint(Y)+size]])``, before calling ``rt = photometry(image=image, positions=pos)``. Also, you can just do ``photometry.aperture_radius = value`` to change the value of ``aperture_radius``.

@stefanocovino, again, thanks for reporting :)

@ChristophBusold 

1. Hum, this makes sense. But I still don’t understand why this option exist then. So you check upstream OCSP, and then what? Discard if it doesn’t work? But with must-staple, that won’t work. And the client is going to check the answer anyway, so…
2. I have no idea (for both questions)…

@bitinn Why is using an external resolver is better security and performance wise? Anyway, I’ve just tested without `ssl_trusted_certificate` and `8.8.8.8` as `resolver`, and it worked.

And you exactly need one request for OCSP to kick in, that’s because Nginx doesn’t have the answer cached on start.

Now regarding the root certificate, it should not be part of the chain/fullchain. And I’m wondering if the people having issues here have the root certificate in their system trust store… You’re not supposed to have to download it from somewhere, it should be provided by your OS.

