@rmorshea this PR however *also* makes ipywidgets incompatible with traitlets < 5, which is a problem because then both packages must be released at the exact same time (ipywidgets 6 is incompatible with traitlets 5 and ipywidgets 7 is incompatible with traitlets 4). We should never require coordinated releases across Jupyter projects. Every new release of a given Jupyter package should work with the current stable version of every other package at time of release. To that end, *master* of every package should endeavor to work with stable of every other package.

For instance: if traitlets 5 will break widgets, we need to make a new release of widgets that works with traitlets master *before* releasing traitlets 5. In order for that release of ipywidgets to work, though, it must *also* work with the current stable version of traitlets, otherwise we will be releasing a package that cannot be installed due to unsatisfiable dependencies.

One way to make such a fix: check for the presence of `has_trait_value` and only call it if it's defined. That way, the 4.x behavior remains unchanged, and the extra check is only applied once traitlets is updated.

@JackUrb  Just to make my understanding clear:

For UpdateHandler, we need to update the `update_window` function so that it returns the `(updated_window, updated_data)` and to appropriately include it in the packet `p`.

This can be achieved by comparing the incoming data with the existing data on the handler and then mark the changes in the packet as well.

I was able to satisfy this use case using the `@post_dump` decorator.

```py
@post_dump(pass_original=True)
def filter_links(self, data, car):
    if car.running:
        del data['_links']['start']
    else:
        del data['_links']['stop']
```

The `pass_original` option is only really necessary if the condition requires data that was excluded by the schema. If you can, you may want to avoid it when working with lists due to https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/issues/315.

You can pass a dictionary to `ValidationError` containing the correct pointer:

```python
            raise ValidationError([
                {
                    'detail': '`id` object must be of type `string`.',
                    'source': {
                        'pointer': '/data/id'
                    }
                }
            ])

